Abstract: This paper reports on some evidence from an international consumer survey in Germany and the United States which suggests the existence of an information-sensitive consumer-elite which transcends national boundaries. These Cosmopolitan Information Seekers, far higher in education, income, and social prestige than &ldquo;average&rdquo; consumers, represent a growing nucleus of &ldquo;professional&rdquo; consumers in the industrially advanced countries. The article also explores some of the implications which this segment has for the multinational corporation and the design of its marketing mix.&copy; 1976 JIBS. Journal of International Business Studies (1976) 7, 77&ndash;90
